          ],
          "id": "node-1772570870418-copy-1773951665423-copy-1773951673468",
          "type": "conversation",
          "display_position": {
            "x": -1355.8535232262002,
            "y": -167.50707066552377
          },
          "instruction": {
            "type": "prompt",
            "text": "Ask the user for their full name — first and last name.\n\nSay something like: \"Could I get your full name, please?\"\n\nIf the user only gives a first name (e.g. \"Bob\"), ask for the last name too: \"And your last name, Bob?\"\n\nIf the user only gives a last name or it's unclear which is which, clarify: \"Just to be sure — what's your first name?\"\n\nConfirmation — only when needed:\n- If the name is common and clearly heard (e.g. \"Bob Jones\", \"Maria Garcia\"), just acknowledge it and move on: \n  \"Great, thanks Bob!\"\n- If the name is unusual, has an ambiguous spelling, or the user seemed to struggle saying it, read it back: \"Just to make sure I have it right — that's [First] [Last]?\" - If the user spells it out or corrects you, always confirm the corrected version: \"Got it — [corrected name].\"\n\nIf the user gives a middle name as well, acknowledge it but focus on first and last: \"Thanks! I'll have you down as \n[First] [Last].\"\n\nIf the user refuses to provide their name: Explain why it's needed: \"I completely understand — I only ask because the clinic needs your name to set up the appointment and pull \nup your records. It's kept totally confidential.\"\n\nDo NOT ask more than twice."
          }
        },
